==History== {{Expand section|date=November 2016}}
The ''Tátra'' class comprised six ships - ''Tátra'', ''Balaton'', ''Csepel'', ''Lika'', ''Triglav'' and ''Orjen''. Built by [[Porto Ré]], a subsidiary of [[Danubius & Ganz]], they were launched in the years 1912 and 1913. ''Triglav'' and ''Lika'' were sunk by [[naval mine|mine]]s near [[Durazzo]] on 29 December 1915.
Six further destroyers were authorised in May 1914 to increase the number of destroyers, but construction had not started at the outbreak of the war. Four units were authorised in 1916 to replace the wartime losses. These four ships were named ''Triglav II'', ''Lika II'', ''Dukla'' and ''Uzsok'' and classified as the '''Replacement Triglav Class'''. They were also built by Danubius and launched in 1917, so their wartime careers were rather short. Propelled by two [[steam turbines]] these four vessels were the most modern ships of the Austro-Hungarian Navy.
After the war, three vessels—''Triglav'', ''Lika'', and ''Uzsok''—were ceded to [[Italy]] and one, ''Dukla'', to [[France]]. The last vessel was scrapped in 1936.
== Design == {{Expand section|date=November 2016}}
The ships were of {{convert|85.28|m|ft|abbr=on}} overall length with a beam of {{convert|7.80|m|ft|abbr=on}}. Their design displacement was 880 tons{{citation needed|date=February 2010|reason=Fitzsimons says 870 normal}} with a full load displacement of 1050 tons. Powered by two [[AEG-Curtiss]] turbines producing {{convert|20600|shp|MW|abbr=on}}, driving two shafts. They were able to achieve speeds of up to {{convert|33.8|kn|km/h}}. Of the six [[Yarrow Shipbuilders|Yarrow]] boilers, four were [[petroleum|oil]]-fired and the other two capable of operating with either oil or [[coal]].
Their armament was two 100&nbsp;mm 50 [[Caliber#Caliber as measurement of length|calibre]] guns. Secondary armament was provided by six 66&nbsp;mm 45 calibre guns. Two of these were on special [[anti-aircraft]] mountings. The gun armament was completed by a single {{convert|7.8|mm|in|abbr=on|adj=on}} machine gun.{{citation needed|date=February 2010}} Their main offensive capability came from four {{convert|450|mm|in|abbr=on|adj=on}} [[torpedo tube]]s mounted in pairs.
